    <h1>Anchor Text Options for Integrated Literacy Intervention</h1>
    <p>The following 40 texts are organized by complexity level and feature various affixes aligned with Indiana's 3rd grade standards. Each text includes identified target affixes, Lexile level, and main idea/supporting details focus.</p>

    <h2>LOW COMPLEXITY TEXTS (460L-600L)</h2>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>1. Helpful Animals</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 460L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Service animals helping people">
        <p>Service animals are <span class="affix-highlight">helpful</span> to people every day. Dogs can be <span class="affix-highlight">trained</span> to help people who cannot see. These <span class="affix-highlight">special</span> dogs wear <span class="affix-highlight">harnesses</span> that keep them <span class="affix-highlight">connected</span> to their owners. Some service animals help people who feel <span class="affix-highlight">unsafe</span> or <span class="affix-highlight">fearful</span>. Other animals can <span class="affix-highlight">remind</span> people to take medicine or help them walk. These <span class="affix-highlight">amazing</span> animals make life <span class="affix-highlight">easier</span> for many people.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ful (helpful), -ed (trained), -al (special), -ness (harness), -ed (connected), un- (unsafe), -ful (fearful), re- (remind), -ing (amazing), -er (easier)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Service animals help people in different ways</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Guiding the blind, helping with fear, reminding about medicine, making mobility easier</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>2. Weather Watchers</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 480L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Weather instruments and meteorologists">
        <p>Weather <span class="affix-highlight">forecasters</span> help us know what to expect each day. They use many <span class="affix-highlight">helpful</span> tools to <span class="affix-highlight">predict</span> if it will rain or shine. Some tools <span class="affix-highlight">measure</span> how much rain has <span class="affix-highlight">fallen</span>. Others <span class="affix-highlight">record</span> how fast the wind is <span class="affix-highlight">blowing</span>. Weather <span class="affix-highlight">satellites</span> take pictures from space to show clouds <span class="affix-highlight">moving</span> across Earth. With all this <span class="affix-highlight">information</span>, <span class="affix-highlight">forecasters</span> can tell us if we need an <span class="affix-highlight">umbrella</span> or <span class="affix-highlight">sunscreen</span>!</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -er (forecaster), -ful (helpful), pre- (predict), -ure (measure), -en (fallen), re- (record), -ing (blowing), -ite (satellite), -ing (moving), -tion (information), -er (forecaster), -ella (umbrella), sun- (sunscreen)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Weather forecasters use different tools to predict weather</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Tools that measure rain, record wind, satellites that take pictures from space</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>3. Underground Homes</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 490L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Animals in underground burrows">
        <p>Many animals make their homes <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span>. Rabbits dig <span class="affix-highlight">burrows</span> with many <span class="affix-highlight">tunnels</span> and rooms. These <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span> homes keep rabbits <span class="affix-highlight">safer</span> from <span class="affix-highlight">predators</span> that want to eat them. Ants build <span class="affix-highlight">amazing</span> <span class="affix-highlight">colonies</span> with <span class="affix-highlight">hundreds</span> of <span class="affix-highlight">connected</span> tunnels. Prairie dogs create whole <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span> towns where they live <span class="affix-highlight">together</span>. Being <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span> helps these animals stay <span class="affix-highlight">cooler</span> in summer and <span class="affix-highlight">warmer</span> in winter.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> under- (underground), -ow (burrow), -el (tunnel), under- (underground), -er (safer), pre- (predator), -ing (amazing), -ies (colonies), -ed (connected), under- (underground), to- (together), under- (underground), -er (cooler), -er (warmer)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Many animals create homes underground for protection and comfort</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Rabbits dig burrows, ants build colonies, prairie dogs create towns, underground homes provide temperature control</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>4. The Water Cycle</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 510L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Water cycle diagram">
        <p>Water is always <span class="affix-highlight">moving</span> around our Earth in a cycle. The sun <span class="affix-highlight">heats</span> water in oceans, lakes, and rivers. The <span class="affix-highlight">heated</span> water turns into water vapor and <span class="affix-highlight">rises</span> into the sky. This is called <span class="affix-highlight">evaporation</span>. As water vapor <span class="affix-highlight">cools</span>, it forms clouds through <span class="affix-highlight">condensation</span>. When clouds get too <span class="affix-highlight">heavy</span>, water <span class="affix-highlight">falls</span> back to Earth as rain or snow. This is <span class="affix-highlight">precipitation</span>. The water then <span class="affix-highlight">collects</span> in oceans, lakes, and rivers, and the cycle <span class="affix-highlight">restarts</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ing (moving), -s (heats), -ed (heated), -es (rises), -tion (evaporation), -s (cools), -tion (condensation), -y (heavy), -s (falls), pre- (precipitation), col- (collects), re- (restarts)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Water constantly moves through a cycle on Earth</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Evaporation of water into vapor, condensation into clouds, precipitation back to Earth's surface</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>5. Recycling Matters</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 520L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Recycling bins and process">
        <p><span class="affix-highlight">Recycling</span> means using things again instead of <span class="affix-highlight">throwing</span> them away. Many items we use daily can be <span class="affix-highlight">recycled</span>. Paper can be <span class="affix-highlight">reused</span> to make new paper products. Plastic bottles can be <span class="affix-highlight">remade</span> into new bottles or <span class="affix-highlight">clothing</span>. Metal cans are <span class="affix-highlight">melted</span> down and <span class="affix-highlight">reshaped</span>. <span class="affix-highlight">Recycling</span> helps keep our planet <span class="affix-highlight">cleaner</span> and <span class="affix-highlight">healthier</span>. It also <span class="affix-highlight">reduces</span> the amount of trash in <span class="affix-highlight">landfills</span>. When we <span class="affix-highlight">recycle</span>, we are being <span class="affix-highlight">helpful</span> to Earth.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> re- (recycling), -ing (throwing), re- (recycled), re- (reused), re- (remade), -ing (clothing), -ed (melted), re- (reshaped), re- (recycling), -er (cleaner), -er (healthier), re- (reduces), land- (landfills), re- (recycle), -ful (helpful)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Recycling helps the environment by reusing materials</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Paper can be reused, plastic can be remade into new products, metal can be melted and reshaped, recycling reduces landfill waste</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>6. Plant Parts</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 530L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Plant diagram showing parts">
        <p>Plants have many important parts that help them grow and live. The <span class="affix-highlight">roots</span> grow <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span> and take in water and <span class="affix-highlight">nutrients</span>. The stem <span class="affix-highlight">supports</span> the plant and <span class="affix-highlight">carries</span> water up to the leaves. Leaves are like solar panels that <span class="affix-highlight">collect</span> sunlight to make food in a process called <span class="affix-highlight">photosynthesis</span>. Many plants grow <span class="affix-highlight">colorful</span> flowers that <span class="affix-highlight">attract</span> <span class="affix-highlight">pollinators</span> like bees and <span class="affix-highlight">butterflies</span>. After <span class="affix-highlight">pollination</span>, flowers turn into fruits or seeds that can grow into new plants.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -s (roots), under- (underground), -ent (nutrients), -s (supports), -ies (carries), col- (collect), photo- (photosynthesis), -ful (colorful), at- (attract), -or (pollinator), butter- (butterfly), -tion (pollination)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Plants have different parts with specific functions</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Roots collect water and nutrients, stems support and transport, leaves collect sunlight, flowers attract pollinators</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>7. Animal Coverings</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 540L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Various animal coverings">
        <p>Animals have different types of <span class="affix-highlight">coverings</span> that <span class="affix-highlight">protect</span> them. Birds have <span class="affix-highlight">feathers</span> that keep them <span class="affix-highlight">warm</span> and help them fly. Fish have <span class="affix-highlight">scales</span> that <span class="affix-highlight">overlap</span> like tiny <span class="affix-highlight">shields</span>. Mammals have fur or hair that can be <span class="affix-highlight">thick</span> or <span class="affix-highlight">thin</span> <span class="affix-highlight">depending</span> on where they live. Some animals like turtles have <span class="affix-highlight">hardened</span> shells for <span class="affix-highlight">protection</span>. Insects have <span class="affix-highlight">exoskeletons</span>, which are hard <span class="affix-highlight">coverings</span> on the <span class="affix-highlight">outside</span> of their bodies. These <span class="affix-highlight">different</span> <span class="affix-highlight">coverings</span> help animals <span class="affix-highlight">survive</span> in their homes.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ing (covering), pro- (protect), -er (feather), -m (warm), -s (scales), over- (overlap), -s (shields), -ck (thick), -in (thin), de- (depending), -en (hardened), -tion (protection), exo- (exoskeleton), -ing (covering), out- (outside), dif- (different), -ing (covering), sur- (survive)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Animals have different coverings that serve important purposes</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Birds have feathers, fish have scales, mammals have fur, turtles have shells, insects have exoskeletons</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>8. Super Senses</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 550L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Animals using their senses">
        <p>Animals have <span class="affix-highlight">amazing</span> senses that help them <span class="affix-highlight">survive</span>. Dogs have an <span class="affix-highlight">incredible</span> sense of smell that is much <span class="affix-highlight">stronger</span> than ours. They can <span class="affix-highlight">detect</span> smells that are <span class="affix-highlight">invisible</span> to people. Eagles have <span class="affix-highlight">powerful</span> <span class="affix-highlight">eyesight</span> and can see tiny animals from high in the sky. Bats use <span class="affix-highlight">echolocation</span>, <span class="affix-highlight">sending</span> out sounds that <span class="affix-highlight">bounce</span> back to help them "see" in the dark. Some snakes can <span class="affix-highlight">sense</span> heat, <span class="affix-highlight">allowing</span> them to find warm animals even at night when it's <span class="affix-highlight">completely</span> dark.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ing (amazing), sur- (survive), in- (incredible), -er (stronger), de- (detect), in- (invisible), -ful (powerful), -sight (eyesight), echo- (echolocation), -ing (sending), -ce (bounce), -se (sense), -ing (allowing), com- (completely)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Animals have specialized senses that help them survive</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Dogs have strong smell, eagles have powerful vision, bats use echolocation, snakes sense heat</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>9. Money Basics</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 560L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Coins and bills">
        <p>Money helps us buy things we need and want. People <span class="affix-highlight">earn</span> money by <span class="affix-highlight">working</span> at jobs. When you <span class="affix-highlight">receive</span> money, you can <span class="affix-highlight">spend</span> it, <span class="affix-highlight">save</span> it, or <span class="affix-highlight">donate</span> it. <span class="affix-highlight">Saving</span> means <span class="affix-highlight">keeping</span> money for <span class="affix-highlight">later</span> use, like <span class="affix-highlight">buying</span> something <span class="affix-highlight">special</span>. <span class="affix-highlight">Spending</span> means using money to get something now. <span class="affix-highlight">Donating</span> means <span class="affix-highlight">giving</span> money to help others. It's <span class="affix-highlight">important</span> to make <span class="affix-highlight">thoughtful</span> choices about how to use money because it is <span class="affix-highlight">limited</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -rn (earn), -ing (working), re- (receive), -nd (spend), -ve (save), -ate (donate), -ing (saving), -ing (keeping), -er (later), -ing (buying), -al (special), -ing (spending), -ing (donating), -ing (giving), im- (important), -ful (thoughtful), -ed (limited)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Money can be earned and used in different ways</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> People earn money through work, money can be spent now, saved for later, or donated to help others</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>10. How Seeds Travel</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 570L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Seeds traveling by various methods">
        <p>Plants cannot move, but their seeds can <span class="affix-highlight">travel</span> in <span class="affix-highlight">surprising</span> ways. Some seeds have <span class="affix-highlight">parachutes</span> made of fluff that help them <span class="affix-highlight">float</span> on the wind. Dandelion seeds are <span class="affix-highlight">carried</span> this way. Some plants have seeds with <span class="affix-highlight">hooks</span> that <span class="affix-highlight">attach</span> to animal fur or people's <span class="affix-highlight">clothing</span>. These <span class="affix-highlight">hitchhikers</span> can <span class="affix-highlight">travel</span> far from their parent plant. Some plants <span class="affix-highlight">package</span> their seeds in <span class="affix-highlight">tasty</span> fruits. When animals eat the fruit, they <span class="affix-highlight">deposit</span> the seeds later in a new place. Water can also <span class="affix-highlight">transport</span> seeds to new <span class="affix-highlight">locations</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -el (travel), sur- (surprising), para- (parachute), -at (float), -ed (carried), -s (hooks), at- (attach), -ing (clothing), hitch- (hitchhiker), -el (travel), -age (package), -y (tasty), de- (deposit), trans- (transport), -tion (location)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Seeds travel away from parent plants in different ways</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Some seeds float on wind, attach to animals, get eaten and deposited elsewhere, or float on water</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>11. Animal Homes</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 580L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Different animal habitats">
        <p>Animals build many <span class="affix-highlight">different</span> kinds of homes. Birds make nests by <span class="affix-highlight">collecting</span> twigs, grass, and other <span class="affix-highlight">materials</span>. Beavers are <span class="affix-highlight">famous</span> <span class="affix-highlight">builders</span> that cut down trees with their teeth to make dams and lodges. Some animals dig <span class="affix-highlight">underground</span> homes called burrows. Rabbits and <span class="affix-highlight">groundhogs</span> are good <span class="affix-highlight">diggers</span>. Bees work <span class="affix-highlight">together</span> to build <span class="affix-highlight">honeycomb</span> homes with many <span class="affix-highlight">hexagonal</span> rooms. Hermit crabs don't build homes at allâ€”they find empty shells and move <span class="affix-highlight">inside</span> them. Each animal's home helps it <span class="affix-highlight">survive</span> in its <span class="affix-highlight">environment</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> dif- (different), col- (collecting), -al (material), -ous (famous), -er (builder), under- (underground), ground- (groundhog), -er (digger), to- (together), honey- (honeycomb), hexa- (hexagonal), in- (inside), sur- (survive), -ment (environment)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Animals create or find different types of homes</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Birds build nests, beavers construct dams and lodges, some animals dig burrows, bees create honeycombs, hermit crabs use shells</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>12. All About Teeth</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 585L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Teeth and dental care">
        <p>Your teeth help you eat, speak, and smile. Each tooth has a hard <span class="affix-highlight">outer</span> <span class="affix-highlight">covering</span> called enamel that <span class="affix-highlight">protects</span> it. <span class="affix-highlight">Inside</span> each tooth are nerves that let you feel hot, cold, and pain. <span class="affix-highlight">Different</span> teeth have <span class="affix-highlight">different</span> jobs. <span class="affix-highlight">Front</span> teeth help <span class="affix-highlight">bite</span> food, while <span class="affix-highlight">back</span> teeth <span class="affix-highlight">grind</span> and <span class="affix-highlight">crush</span> it. <span class="affix-highlight">Keeping</span> your teeth <span class="affix-highlight">healthy</span> means <span class="affix-highlight">brushing</span> twice a day and <span class="affix-highlight">flossing</span> to <span class="affix-highlight">remove</span> food that gets <span class="affix-highlight">stuck</span> <span class="affix-highlight">between</span> teeth. <span class="affix-highlight">Regular</span> <span class="affix-highlight">checkups</span> with a <span class="affix-highlight">dentist</span> also help keep your smile <span class="affix-highlight">bright</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> out- (outer), -ing (covering), pro- (protects), in- (inside), dif- (different), dif- (different), front- (front), -te (bite), back- (back), -nd (grind), -sh (crush), -ing (keeping), -y (healthy), -ing (brushing), -ing (flossing), re- (remove), -ck (stuck), be- (between), -ar (regular), check- (checkup), -ist (dentist), -ght (bright)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Teeth have different parts and functions that require proper care</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Teeth have protective enamel, different teeth have different jobs, teeth need regular brushing and flossing, dental checkups are important</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>13. Mighty Muscles</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 590L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Human muscular system">
        <p>Your body has over 600 muscles that help you move and do <span class="affix-highlight">activities</span>. Muscles work by <span class="affix-highlight">contracting</span> (getting <span class="affix-highlight">shorter</span>) and <span class="affix-highlight">relaxing</span> (getting <span class="affix-highlight">longer</span>). Some muscles you can control, like the ones that help you <span class="affix-highlight">walk</span>, <span class="affix-highlight">jump</span>, and <span class="affix-highlight">smile</span>. Other muscles work <span class="affix-highlight">automatically</span>, like your heart, which is a <span class="affix-highlight">powerful</span> muscle that pumps blood. <span class="affix-highlight">Exercise</span> makes muscles <span class="affix-highlight">stronger</span> and <span class="affix-highlight">healthier</span>. When you <span class="affix-highlight">stretch</span> before <span class="affix-highlight">activity</span>, you help <span class="affix-highlight">prevent</span> <span class="affix-highlight">injuries</span>. <span class="affix-highlight">Resting</span> is also important because it gives muscles time to <span class="affix-highlight">repair</span> and grow.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ity (activity), con- (contracting), -er (shorter), re- (relaxing), -er (longer), -lk (walk), -mp (jump), -le (smile), auto- (automatically), -ful (powerful), ex- (exercise), -er (stronger), -er (healthier), -ch (stretch), -ity (activity), pre- (prevent), -ies (injuries), -ing (resting), re- (repair)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Muscles have important functions and need proper care</p>
            <p><strong>Supporting Details:</strong> Muscles contract and relax to create movement, some muscles are voluntary while others work automatically, exercise strengthens muscles, rest helps muscles repair</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-option">
        <h3>14. Insect Bodies</h3>
        <span class="level low">Low: 595L</span>
        <img src="/api/placeholder/400/200" alt="Insect body parts labeled">
        <p>Insects are the most <span class="affix-highlight">successful</span> animals on Earth, with more kinds than any other animal group. All insects have three main body parts: the head, thorax, and <span class="affix-highlight">abdomen</span>. On their heads, insects have two <span class="affix-highlight">antennae</span> for <span class="affix-highlight">sensing</span> their <span class="affix-highlight">surroundings</span>. Most insects have <span class="affix-highlight">compound</span> eyes with many tiny <span class="affix-highlight">lenses</span> that help them see in <span class="affix-highlight">different</span> <span class="affix-highlight">directions</span> at once. Insects have six <span class="affix-highlight">jointed</span> legs <span class="affix-highlight">attached</span> to their thorax. Many insects have wings, which let them fly. Insects grow by <span class="affix-highlight">molting</span>, <span class="affix-highlight">shedding</span> their hard <span class="affix-highlight">exoskeleton</span> as they get <span class="affix-highlight">bigger</span>.</p>
        <div class="text-details">
            <p><strong>Target Affixes:</strong> -ful (successful), ab- (abdomen), -ae (antennae), -ing (sensing), sur- (surroundings), com- (compound), -es (lenses), dif- (different), -tion (direction), -ed (jointed), at- (attached), -ing (molting), -ing (shedding), exo- (exoskeleton), -er (bigger)</p>
            <p><strong>Main Idea:</strong> Insects
